<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">The unit's anchor question: <em>How do you build for a planet that occasionally tries to destroy what you've built?</em></p>
  <p>Earth's surface tells a story 4.5 billion years in the making — and most of it is written in the language of moving plates. Before you can engineer a city against tectonic hazards, you have to know what's actually moving and why. Today we set the foundation: Earth's interior, what drives plate motion, and the four boundary types that produce every major hazard family you'll meet in this unit. You'll also meet your first Unit 3 AI partner — <strong>The Plate Tectonics Tutor</strong>, a coach for boundary mechanics that asks questions before it hands you answers.</p>
  <p>By the end of class you should be able to look at a world map and explain why earthquakes cluster where they do — and why some coasts get tsunamis while others don't.</p>
</section>

